 <div class="title" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">SIMULATION RESULTS</div>
 <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">To perform the simulations, we are going to assume that one can prepare the states from the two oriented molecular beams into the combinations ∣
  <span class="italic">H</span>〉 ∣ 
  <span class="italic">H</span>〉; ∣
  <span class="italic">V</span>〉 ∣ 
  <span class="italic">V</span>〉 and ∣ + 〉 ∣ + 〉, ∣ − 〉 ∣ − 〉 and, finally, the Werner state
  <div id="E12" class="disp-formula">
   <div id="m43" class="math">
    <div class="mrow">
     <div class="mrow">
      <div class="msub">
       <span mathvariant="normal" class="mi">ρ</span>
       <span class="mi">w</span>
      </div>
      <span stretchy="false" class="mo">(</span>
      <span class="mi">p</span>
      <span stretchy="false" class="mo">)</span>
      <span class="mo">=</span>
      <div class="mfrac">
       <span class="mi">p</span>
       <span class="mn">2</span>
      </div>
      <span stretchy="false" class="mo">(</span>
      <span class="mo"> </span>
      <span class="mo">∣</span>
      <span mathvariant="italic" class="mi">HV</span>
      <span stretchy="false" class="mo">〉</span>
      <span class="mo">+</span>
      <span class="mo">∣</span>
      <span mathvariant="italic" class="mi">VH</span>
      <span stretchy="false" class="mo">〉</span>
      <span class="mo"> </span>
      <span stretchy="false" class="mo">)</span>
      <span stretchy="false" class="mo">(</span>
      <span class="mo"> </span>
      <span stretchy="false" class="mo">〈</span>
      <span mathvariant="italic" class="mi">HV</span>
      <span class="mo">∣</span>
      <span class="mo">+</span>
      <span stretchy="false" class="mo">〈</span>
      <span mathvariant="italic" class="mi">VH</span>
      <span class="mo">∣</span>
      <span class="mo"> </span>
      <span stretchy="false" class="mo">)</span>
      <span class="mo">+</span>
      <div class="mfrac">
       <div class="mrow">
        <span class="mn">1</span>
        <span class="mo">−</span>
        <span class="mi">p</span>
       </div>
       <span class="mn">4</span>
      </div>
      <span class="mi">I</span>
     </div>
    </div>
   </div>
   <span class="label">(12)</span>
  </div>
 </p>
 <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">The free parameter 
  <span class="italic">p</span> describes entanglement of the Werner state. 
  <span class="italic">p</span> = 0 indicates separability, entanglement for 
  <span class="italic">p</span> ≤ 1/3, and Bell states of maximum entanglement at 
  <span class="italic">p</span> = 1 (
  <a rid="R37" ref-type="bibr" href="#R37">
   <span class="italic">37</span>
  </a>).
 </p>
 <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">If enough HD molecule pairs are prepared as mentioned above, then the predicted spectra for different initial states are shown in 
  <a rid="F3" ref-type="fig" href="#F3">Fig. 3</a>. The simulation is based on data of scattering experiment between HD and H
  <sub>2</sub> clusters taken from (
  <a rid="R30" ref-type="bibr" href="#R30">
   <span class="italic">30</span>
  </a>) (scattering spectrum; 
  <a rid="F4" ref-type="fig" href="#F4">Fig. 4, A and B</a>).
 </p>
 <div id="F3" fig-type="figure" orientation="portrait" position="float" class="fig" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
  <span class="label">Fig. 3</span>
  <div class="caption">
   <div class="title">Simulation results of the scattering experiments.</div>
